trend_summary: Across the series, built-up land gradually enlarges yet stays interspersed with woodland. New warehouses and retail pads cluster near the southeastern highway knot, residential cul-de-sacs infill interior blocks, and main roads gain extra lanes and ramps. Some riverside factories are replaced with lighter commercial uses and green buffers. Overall character: medium-density, automobile-oriented suburbia.
notable_changes: Construction of a large white-roof logistics/warehouse park beside the southeastern freeway interchange.
Upgrade of the river-parallel expressway and addition of cloverleaf ramps and collector lanes.
Incremental infill of new residential streets and cul-de-sacs north of the river.
Redevelopment of older riverside industrial lots into lighter commercial premises with more parking.
Expansion of tree cover in the northwest as former open fields transition to woodland or parkland.
